An extension CRX package can traverse local directory paths by using 
malformed UTF8 filenames in the CRX zip archive. Invalid UTF8 filename 
characters are removed by a UTF8 to UTF16 conversion, which occurs after 
&quot;..&quot; traversal checking. So, a UTF8 path might contain a sequence like 
&quot;/.X./.X./&quot; where X is an invalid value like 0x80. After conversion to 
UTF16, this sequence collapses to &quot;/../../&quot;. 

This appears to be Windows only, and occurs before validation, during 
unpacking. The temporary directory is at a known depth, so it would be 
possible to drop a file in any standard path. I've confirmed this in the 
debugger, but haven't made a repro. 

The fix should be as simple moving the &quot;..&quot; check to after the UTF16 
conversion in ExtractCurrentFile(). I'd also suggest we insert the Unicode 
substitution character on errors in ConvertUnicode() (as mentioned in the 
code comments). However, the Unicode change has broader impact and might 
need additional validation.



