The explanation is as follows. In ExtractCurrentFile() we check the 
supplied zip filename while it's encoded as UTF8:

  // Check the filename here for directory traversal issues. In the name of
  // simplicity and security, we might reject a valid filename such as 
&quot;a..b&quot;
  if (strstr(filename_inzip, &quot;..&quot;) != NULL)
    return false;


Then we convert from UTF8 to UTF16:

#if defined(OS_WIN)
  filename = UTF8ToWide(filename_inzip);


ConvertUnicode() skips invalid characters and continues processing:

  for (int32 i = 0; i &lt; src_len32; i++) {
    uint32 code_point;
    if (ReadUnicodeCharacter(src, src_len32, &amp;i, &amp;code_point)) {
      WriteUnicodeCharacter(code_point, output);
    } else {
      // TODO(jungshik): consider adding 'Replacement character' (U+FFFD)
      // in place of an invalid codepoint.
      success = false;
    }


And the top level UTF8ToWide() returns the resulting string without 
notifying the caller of the error:

std::wstring UTF8ToWide(const base::StringPiece&amp; utf8) {
  std::wstring ret;
  UTF8ToWide(utf8.data(), utf8.length(), &amp;ret);
  return ret;
}

ChromeFrame version: all

Related URL(s): http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/chrome-
frame/1.0.1/CFInstall.js

<b>Steps to reproduce the issue:</b>
1. implement the user agent detection via cfinstall.js on a site
2. visit in IE 6 sp2
3. observe the prompt is not displayed

<b>What do you expect to happen?</b>

The prompt should be shown

<b>What do you see instead?</b>

No prompt.

The problem seems to be with this chunk of code:

      if (parseFloat(ua.split(ieRe)[1]) &lt; 6 &amp;&amp;
          ua.indexOf('SV1') &gt;= 0) {
        bail = true;
      }

Which SHOULD read:

      if (parseFloat(ua.split(ieRe)[1]) &lt; 6 &amp;&amp;
          ua.indexOf('SV1') &lt; 0) { // SV1 missing
        bail = true;
      }

Right now, these methods are not implemented and fail silently. Darin has 
requested that we attempt to implement them asynchronously instead of the 
standard synchronous versions.

So, the signatures would look like:

// The alert is non-blocking. If callback, is specified, it gets called
// after the alert is dismissed.
alert(message, [callback()])

// The alerts are non-blocking and the callbacks are required.
prompt(message, default, callback(result))
confirm(message, callback(bool_result))

The following code opens two sites, the first one ends up in a blocked pop-
up, the second one in a new tab (through another blocked pop-up):
&lt;SCRIPT&gt;
  window.open('http://good.com');
  window.open(&quot;javascript:window.open('http://evil.com');&quot;);
&lt;/SCRIPT&gt;

Tested with 2.0.172.37 and 3.0.196.0 (21522)

This does not affect Safari.

Our 2 ways of opening channels is inconsistent:
  int chrome.extension.connect(string name);
  int chrome.tabs.connect(int tabId, object with string name);

We should change the former to:
  int chrome.extension.connect([string extensionId], object with string 
name);

If extensionId is not specified, it should default to the current extension.

